},{"name":"Lee","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Young, Sang, Jae, Jong, Jung, Sung, Yong, Kyung, Seung, Dong, Kwang, Myung.","English: topographic name for someone who lived near a meadow or a patch of arable land, Middle English <i>lee</i>, <i>lea</i>, from Old English <i>lēa</i>, dative case (used after a preposition) of <i>lēah</i>, which originally meant ‘wood or glade’.","English: habitational name from any of the many places in England named with Old English <i>lēah</i> ‘wood, glade’, including Lee in Buckinghamshire, Essex, Hampshire, Kent, and Shropshire, and Lea in Cheshire, Derbyshire, Herefordshire, Lancashire, Lincolnshire, and Wiltshire."]}]},{"name":"Katherine","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Greek: Same as Catherine."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":22,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705197,"age":95,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Katherine Leigh was born in 1360, in Cumberland, England, her father, Sir Thomas Leigh, was 20 and her mother, Lady Margaret Davenport, was 5. She married Sir John De Ireby sheriff in 1374, in High I